This document explains how to retrieve and use the cross-sectional design weights in the SHARE data. All R code can be shown by selecting Code/Show all code in the top right corner of the document, or individual chunks can be displayed or hidden using the Code/Hidden buttons that appear on the right of the text. The research question is described in detail in Part 2, where the data used in regression models were retrieved.

The packages and support functions used for the analyses are listed in the code below.

1 Survey weights in SHARE data

In SHARE study the sampling designs differ substantially across participating countries, from simple random sampling to multistage designs.

Both study design weights and calibrated weights are available. Study design weights take into account the selection probabilities, but their usage is discouraged, due to unit non-response and sample attrition at each follow-up. Calibrated weights are re-weighted design weights that take the unit non-response into account and their use is advocated for inference to the target population.

The modules specific to weights include also variables that indicate the strata (stratum variables) and the primary sampling units (psu) (the availability differs depending on the sampling strategy of the region).

Using survey weights may give more appropriate or representative results to describe the target population, but fitting unweighted regression models can often provide acceptable estimates. When weighted and unweighted analyses give very different results a sensitivity analysis is recommended [3, sec. 5.3]. We illustrate the use of cross-sectional weights in specific waves, using the functions from the survey and srvyr R packages. The combination of data from different waves requires additional steps for re-weighting the survey weights. This involves careful considerations since there are several ways how this can be achieved. This is out-of-scope for this document, we refer to the references at the end of this file for further information.

Here we discuss only cross-sectional weights (gv_weights modules), but also longitudinal weights are available (gv_weights_longitudinal modules). The target population for the longitudinal analysis is the population surviving up to the time is considered, to take sample attrition due to mortality into account. The longitudinal weights are provided for paired comparisons of adjacent waves or for the analysis of all available waves.

2.1 Retrieving survey weights and joining them with data

The code below retrieves the cross-sectional weights for Wave 5, and joins the data that include the outcome variable and the covariates used in the regression models.

# retrieval of weights from wave 5
share.data.weights <- f_readRShare(
  datadir = "sharedata",
  waves = 5,
  modules = "gv_weights",
  modules.wX = NULL  ,
  countries = NULL,
  variables.in.modules = NULL,
  keep.module.name.in.vars = FALSE,
  verbose = FALSE
)$df.w

# obtain only data from wave 5 from those used to develop the models that include all waves
share.data.w1 <- filter(share.data$df.w, Wave == "Wave 5")
share.data.w1 <- mutate(share.data.w1, age_int_stand = age_int - 50)

# join with variable data
share.data.w1 <-
  left_join(share.data.weights[, c("mergeid",
                                   "dw_w5",
                                   "cciw_w5",
                                   "subsample",
                                   "stratum1",
                                   "stratum2",
                                   "psu",
                                   "ssu")], share.data.w1,  by = "mergeid")

# filter out the observations with missing weights
share.data.w1  <- filter(share.data.w1,!is.na(cciw_w5))


# dropping the participants from Israel
share.data.w1  <- filter(share.data.w1, country != "Israel")

# dropping unused levels
share.data.w1 <- droplevels(share.data.w1)

2.2 Estimation of weighted prevalence of depression

Here we estimate the weighted proportion of participants with depression by region, using the calibrated weights.

The information provided in the gv_weights modules summarize the sampling design for each country, by providing the strata (stratum1 and stratum2) and primary sampling units (psu), when they were used; in our analyses we use individual calibrated weights (cciw_w5), which are design weights re-weighted to compensate for unit-non response.

The table below shows a classification of countries based on the sampling design.

kable(
  share.data.w1 %>% group_by (country) %>% summarise(
    Stratification = any(stratum1 != ""),
    Clustering = any(psu != "")
  ) %>% arrange(Stratification, Clustering),
  caption = "Classification of countries in Wave 5 by use of stratification and clustering"
)  %>% kable_styling()

We specify the sampling design using stratum1 as the stratification variable and psu as the primary sampling unit identifier. For the countries that did not use stratification (stratum1 not specified) we defined a single stratum, for those that did not use clustering (psu not specified) we used a different psu value for each participant.

# assign weights equal to 1 to all participants in an additional variable to obtain unweighted estimates
share.data.w1$wAll1 <- 1


# setting to missing the strata and psu values that are empty
share.data.w1$stratum1[share.data.w1$stratum1 == ""] <- NA
share.data.w1$psu[share.data.w1$psu == ""] <- NA

# number of missing psu
num.na.psu <- sum(is.na(share.data.w1$psu))
share.data.w1$psu <- as.numeric(share.data.w1$psu)

# using constant values for strata within country, all different values of psu for countries that did not have them in the design
share.data.w1$stratum1[is.na(share.data.w1$stratum1)] <-
  paste(share.data.w1$country[is.na(share.data.w1$stratum1)], "fake stratum")
share.data.w1$psu[is.na(share.data.w1$psu)] <-
  c((10 ^ 9 + 1):(10 ^ 9 + num.na.psu))


# specify the sampling design
dstrat <-
  survey::svydesign(
    id =  ~ psu,
    strata =  ~ stratum1,
    weights =  ~ cciw_w5,
    data = share.data.w1,
    nest = TRUE
  )

# id=∼psu specifies sampling at primary sampling unit.
# stratum1 is a factor variable for stratum used for sampling, usually geographical units
# share.data.w1 is the data frame with all the data.
# cciw_w5 contains calibrated sampling weights

# remove the participants not used in the analysis - removed because of missing data or exclusion criteria
dstrat <- subset(dstrat,!is.na(eurodcat_imp))

#to take into account the problem related to strata with a single psu
options(survey.lonely.psu = "adjust")

2.2.1 Estimation of prevalance of depression by gender and region

We estimate the overall weighted prevalence of depression, using weights and taking the sampling design into account, and compare the results obtained without taking weights and sampling design into account.

The weighted prevalence and its standard error are estimated with the svymean function.

# weighted estimate of prevalence
svymean( ~ eurodcat_imp, dstrat, na.rm = TRUE)
##                 mean     SE
## eurodcat_imp 0.28031 0.0042

The unweighted prevalence is about 3 percentage points lower.

Here we show how to fit the weighted logistic regression models with the svyglm function, using the calibrated weights and taking the sampling design into account. The results are summarized graphically and with tables, focusing on the adjusted weighted model, and on the comparison of weighted and unweighted analyses (the code shows how to estimate the weighted/unweighted and adjusted/unadjusted models).

#### Unadjusted models - weighted models and comparison with unweighted
# this model is fitted to derive the basis of the spline for age and save them in the data
my.mod <- lm(
  gender ~ rcs(age_int_stand) ,
  data = share.data.w1[,],
  family = "binomial",
  x = TRUE,
  y = TRUE
)

#save the spline terms in the complete data set for further use
share.data.w1 <- share.data.w1 %>% mutate(
  age1 = my.mod$x[, 2],
  age2 = my.mod$x[, 3],
  age3 = my.mod$x[, 4],
  age4 = my.mod$x[, 5]
)


# retrieve the location of knots used and assign them to Knots variable
Knots <-
  Hmisc::rcspline.eval(x = share.data.w1$age_int_stand,
                       nk = 5,
                       knots.only = TRUE)


# specify the sampling design again, as the age basis variables were added to the dataset
dstrat <-
  survey::svydesign(
    id =  ~ psu,
    strata =  ~ stratum1,
    weights =  ~ cciw_w5,
    data = share.data.w1,
    nest = TRUE
  )

dstrat <- subset(dstrat,!is.na(eurodcat_imp))




# unweighted/unadjusted regression model
my.mod <- glm(
  eurodcat_imp ~ rcs(age_int_stand) + gender + region +
    rcs(age_int_stand):region + rcs(age_int_stand):gender + gender:region ,
  data = share.data.w1,
  family = "binomial",
  x = TRUE,
  y = TRUE
)


# reproduces the spline values for age, expands for each integer value from 50 to 90, using the same knots selected for the complete data
# this dataframe is used in the definition of the grid of values for which the predictions from the models are derived 
age = rcspline.eval(c(50:90) - 50, knots = Knots)
age <- cbind.data.frame(age1 = c(50:90) - 50, age)
dimnames(age)[[2]] <- c("age1", "age2", "age3", "age4")


if (!is.null(my.mod$na.action)) {
  my.mod2 <-
    glm(
      eurodcat_imp ~ age1 + age2 + age3 + age4 + gender + region +
        age1:region + age2:region + age3:region + age4:region +
        age1:gender + age2:gender + age3:gender + age4:gender +
        gender:region ,
      data = share.data.w1[-my.mod$na.action, ],
      family = "binomial",
      x = TRUE,
      y = TRUE
    )
} else {
  my.mod2 <-
    glm(
      eurodcat_imp ~ age1 + age2 + age3 + age4 + gender + region +
        age1:region + age2:region + age3:region + age4:region +
        age1:gender + age2:gender + age3:gender + age4:gender +
        gender:region ,
      data = share.data.w1,
      family = "binomial",
      x = TRUE,
      y = TRUE
    )
}





#derive the data.frame containing the levels of the covariatee, where the probabilities of depression estimated by the model will be derived
data.grid <-
  expand.grid(
    age1 = age[, 1],
    gender = levels(share.data.w1$gender),
    region = levels(share.data.w1$region)
  )
data.grid <- left_join(data.grid, age, by = "age1")


# derive the predicted probabilities
my.pred <-
  predict(my.mod2,
          newdata = data.grid,
          se.fit = TRUE,
          type = "response")

# join the levels of the covariates and the predicted probabilities
my.pred.all <- cbind.data.frame(data.grid, my.pred)

# saving the estimates from the 2-way models
pred.age_unadjusted_region_rcs <- my.pred.all

The estimated OR for the risk factors obtained with weighted and unweighted analysis are similar.

3 Comparison of weighted and unweighted analyses of depression for participants in each wave

Also using the other single waves the results between weighted and unweighted analyses were similar. Using weights had the effect of increasing the variability of the estimates, especially in smaller waves and, when estimating the association between age and probability of depression, at the extremes of the age range.

4 Example: Analysis of the first interviews collected in the wave where the country was first included in the SHARE study

Here we limit the attention to the first interviews collected in the wave when the country was first included in the study. The analysis presented for data for single waves can be easily extended for this problem.

First we subset the data, retrieve the weights for all waves and match the two datasets.

share.data.w1 <- filter(share.data.first.interview, 
                        ( is.element(country, c("Sweden", "Denmark", "Netherlands", "Belgium", "France", "Germany", "Austria", "Switzerland", "Spain", "Italy", "Greece")) & Wave=="Wave 1") |
                          ( is.element(country, c("Ireland", "Czech Republic", "Poland")) & Wave=="Wave 2")|
                          ( is.element(country, c("Portugal", "Hungary", "Slovenia", "Estonia")) & Wave=="Wave 4")|
                          ( is.element(country, c("Luxemburg")) & Wave=="Wave 5") |
                          ( is.element(country, c("Croatia")) & Wave=="Wave 6"))




# retrieval of weights for all waves 
share.data.weights.all <- f_readRShare(
  datadir = "sharedata",
  waves = c(1,2,4,5,6),
  modules = c("gv_weights", "cv_r"),
  modules.wX = NULL  ,
  countries = NULL,
  variables.in.modules = list(gv_weights = NULL, cv_r = c("age_int", "gender", "yrbirth")),
  keep.module.name.in.vars = FALSE,
  verbose = FALSE
)$df.w


# initialization of the weights
share.data.w1$cciw_merged <- rep(-1, nrow(share.data.w1))


# Wave 1
which.obs <- which(is.element(share.data.w1$country, c("Sweden", "Denmark", "Netherlands", "Belgium", "France", "Germany", "Austria", "Switzerland", "Spain", "Italy", "Greece")) & share.data.w1$Wave=="Wave 1")
tmp <- left_join(share.data.w1[which.obs,], share.data.weights.all %>% filter(Wave == "Wave 1") %>% select(c("mergeid", "cciw_w1")), by="mergeid") %>% data.frame()
share.data.w1$cciw_merged[which.obs] <- tmp$cciw_w1
  

# Wave 2
which.obs <- which(is.element(share.data.w1$country, c("Ireland", "Czech Republic", "Poland")) & share.data.w1$Wave=="Wave 2")
tmp <- left_join(share.data.w1[which.obs,], share.data.weights.all %>% filter(Wave == "Wave 2") %>% select(c("mergeid", "cciw_w2")), by="mergeid") %>% data.frame()
share.data.w1$cciw_merged[which.obs] <- tmp$cciw_w2

# Wave 4
which.obs <- which(is.element(share.data.w1$country, c("Portugal", "Hungary", "Slovenia", "Estonia")) & share.data.w1$Wave=="Wave 4")
tmp <- left_join(share.data.w1[which.obs,], share.data.weights.all %>% filter(Wave == "Wave 4") %>% select(c("mergeid", "cciw_w4")), by="mergeid") %>% data.frame()
share.data.w1$cciw_merged[which.obs] <- tmp$cciw_w4

  
# Wave 5
which.obs <- which(is.element(share.data.w1$country, c("Luxemburg")) & share.data.w1$Wave=="Wave 5")
tmp <- left_join(share.data.w1[which.obs,], share.data.weights.all %>% filter(Wave == "Wave 5") %>% select(c("mergeid", "cciw_w5")), by="mergeid") %>% data.frame()
share.data.w1$cciw_merged[which.obs] <- tmp$cciw_w5

# Wave 6
which.obs <- which(is.element(share.data.w1$country, c("Croatia")) & share.data.w1$Wave=="Wave 6")
tmp <- left_join(share.data.w1[which.obs,], share.data.weights.all %>% filter(Wave == "Wave 6") %>% select(c("mergeid", "cciw_w6")), by="mergeid") %>% data.frame()
share.data.w1$cciw_merged[which.obs] <- tmp$cciw_w6
    


share.data.w1 <- filter(share.data.w1, !is.na(cciw_merged))

# retrieving psu and stratum1
share.data.w1 <- left_join(share.data.w1, share.data.weights.all[,c("mergeid", "Wave", "psu", "stratum1")], groupby = c("mergeid", "Wave"))


# setting to missing the strata and psu values that are empty
share.data.w1$stratum1[share.data.w1$stratum1==""] <- NA
share.data.w1$psu[share.data.w1$psu==""] <- NA

# number of missing psu
num.na.psu <- sum(is.na(share.data.w1$psu))
share.data.w1$psu <- as.numeric(share.data.w1$psu)

# using constant values for strata within country, all different values of psu for countries that did not have them in the design
share.data.w1$stratum1[is.na(share.data.w1$stratum1)] <- paste(share.data.w1$country[is.na(share.data.w1$stratum1)], "fake stratum")
share.data.w1$psu[is.na(share.data.w1$psu)] <- c((10^9+1) :  (10^9+num.na.psu)) 



# specify the sampling design
dstrat <- survey::svydesign(id=~psu,strata=~stratum1, weights=~ cciw_merged,
data = share.data.w1, nest=TRUE)

# id=∼psu specifies sampling at primary sampling unit.
# stratum1 is a factor variable for stratum used for sampling, usually geographical units
# share.data.w1 is the data frame with all the data.
# cciw_w1 contains calibrated sampling weights

# remove the participants not used in the analysis - removed because of missing data or exclusion criteria

4.2 Regression models

my.mod <- glm(
  eurodcat_imp ~ rcs(age_int_stand) + gender + region +
    rcs(age_int_stand):region + rcs(age_int_stand):gender + gender:region ,
  data = share.data.w1,
  family = "binomial",
  x = TRUE,
  y = TRUE
)

#save the spline terms in the complete data set for further use
share.data.w1 <- share.data.w1 %>% mutate(
  age1 = my.mod$x[, 2],
  age2 = my.mod$x[, 3],
  age3 = my.mod$x[, 4],
  age4 = my.mod$x[, 5]
)


# retrieve the location of knots used and assign them to Knots variable
Knots <-
  Hmisc::rcspline.eval(x = share.data.w1$age_int_stand,
                       nk = 5,
                       knots.only = TRUE)

#reproduces the spline values for age, expands for each integer value from 50 to 90
age = rcspline.eval(c(50:90) - 50, knots = Knots)
age <- cbind.data.frame(age1 = c(50:90) - 50, age)
dimnames(age)[[2]] <- c("age1", "age2", "age3", "age4")




# specify the sampling design again to use the updated basis for age
dstrat <-
  survey::svydesign(
    id =  ~ psu,
    strata =  ~ stratum1,
    weights =  ~ cciw_merged,
    data = share.data.w1,
    nest = TRUE
  )

# remove the participants not used in the analysis - removed because of missing data or exclusion criteria
dstrat <- subset(dstrat,!is.na(eurodcat_imp))






if (!is.null(my.mod$na.action)) {
  my.mod2 <-
    glm(
      eurodcat_imp ~ age1 + age2 + age3 + age4 + gender + region +
        age1:region + age2:region + age3:region + age4:region +
        age1:gender + age2:gender + age3:gender + age4:gender +
        gender:region ,
      data = share.data.w1[-my.mod$na.action, ],
      family = "binomial",
      x = TRUE,
      y = TRUE
    )
} else {
  my.mod2 <-
    glm(
      eurodcat_imp ~ age1 + age2 + age3 + age4 + gender + region +
        age1:region + age2:region + age3:region + age4:region +
        age1:gender + age2:gender + age3:gender + age4:gender +
        gender:region ,
      data = share.data.w1,
      family = "binomial",
      x = TRUE,
      y = TRUE
    )
}


# derive the data.frame containing the levels of the covariatee, where the probabilities of depression estimated by the model will be derived
data.grid <-
  expand.grid(
    age1 = age[, 1],
    gender = levels(share.data.w1$gender),
    region = levels(share.data.w1$region)
  )
data.grid <- left_join(data.grid, age, by = "age1")


#derive the predicted probabilities
my.pred <-
  predict(my.mod2,
          newdata = data.grid,
          se.fit = TRUE,
          type = "response")

# join the levels of the covariates and the predicted probabilities
my.pred.all <- cbind.data.frame(data.grid, my.pred)

# saving the estimates from the 2-way models
pred.age_unadjusted_region_rcs <- my.pred.all


# weighted unadjusted model
my.mod.w <-
  svyglm(
    eurodcat_imp ~ age1 + age2 + age3 + age4 + gender + region +
      age1:region + age2:region + age3:region + age4:region +
      age1:gender + age2:gender + age3:gender + age4:gender +
      gender:region ,
    design = dstrat,
    family = "binomial",
    x = TRUE,
    y = TRUE
  )




# derive the predicted probabilities
my.pred <-
  predict(my.mod.w,
          newdata = data.grid,
          se.fit = TRUE,
          type = "response")
# join the levels of the covariates and the predicted probabilities
my.pred.all <- cbind.data.frame(data.grid, my.pred)

my.pred.all <-
  pred.age_unadjusted_region_rcs_w <-
  rename(my.pred.all, fit = response, se.fit = SE)
pred.age_unadjusted_region_rcs_w <-
  mutate(pred.age_unadjusted_region_rcs_w, residual.scale = 1)

pred.age_all <-
  rbind.data.frame(pred.age_unadjusted_region_rcs,
                   pred.age_unadjusted_region_rcs_w)
pred.age_all <-
  mutate(pred.age_all, model = c(
    rep("Unadjusted \n rcs", nrow(pred.age_unadjusted_region_rcs)),
    rep(
      "Unadjusted weighted \n rcs",
      nrow(pred.age_unadjusted_region_rcs)
    )
  ))

#saving the estimates from the 2-way models
pred.age_unadjusted_region_rcs <- my.pred.all
